'''Félicien Challaye''' (1875-1967) was a French philosopher and human rights activist.

==Early life==
Félicien Challaye was born on November 1, 1875 in [[Lyon]], France.<ref name="bnf">{{cite web|title=Félicien Challaye (1875-1967)|url=http://data.bnf.fr/12113546/felicien_challaye/|website=[[Bibliothèque nationale de France]]|accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref> He earned the [[Agrégation in France|agrégation]] in Philosophy in 1897.<ref name="bnf"/>

==Career==
Challaye was a high school teacher of philosophy in Paris from 1903 to 1937.<ref name="bnf"/> He served as [[Pierre Savorgnan de Brazza]]'s secretary on his 1905 trip to the [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]].<ref name="entregestesibeud">{{cite journal|last1=Sibeud|first1=Emmanuelle|title=Entre geste impériale et cause internationale : défendre les indigènes à Genève dans les années 1920|journal=Monde(s)|date=2014|volume=2|issue=6|pages=23–43|doi=10.3917/mond.142.0023|url=http://www.cairn.info/article.php?ID_ARTICLE=MOND_142_0023&DocId=299497&hits=10661+10660+9158+9157+8958+8957+7552+7551+4550+4549+3853+3852+3702+3701+2307+2306+2220+2219+|accessdate=August 12, 2016|via=[[Cairn.info]]|registration=yes}}</ref> Three years later, in 1908, he founded a human rights organization for the indigenous people of the Congo.<ref name="entregestesibeud"/> He subsequently served as the vice president of the [[Human Rights League (France)|Human Rights League]].<ref name="bnf"/>

Challaye served in [[World War I]], and he was wounded in combat in 1915.<ref name="lepacifisme12">{{cite journal|last1=Merlio|first1=Gilbert|title=Le pacifisme en Allemagne et en France entre les deux guerres mondiales|journal=Les cahiers Irice|date=2011|volume=2|issue=8|pages=39–59|doi=10.3917/lci.008.0039|url=http://www.cairn.info/article.php?ID_ARTICLE=LCI_008_0039&DocId=162262&hits=6902+6901+6760+6759+6122+6121+|accessdate=August 12, 2016|via=[[Cairn.info]]|registration=yes|quote=Félicien Challaye disciple de Jaurès, blessé en 1915 et converti au pacifisme intégral qu’il défend au sein de la Ligue des droits de l’homme contre Victor Basch, affirme en 1931 vouloir « plutôt l’occupation étrangère que la guerre; et, en 1934, il intitulera un de ses écrits Pour la paix désarmée même face à Hitler.}}</ref> After the war, he became a staunch pacifist.<ref name="pollackunememoire">{{cite journal|last1=Pollack|first1=Guillaume|title=Une mémoire improbable : Jaurès sous l’Occupation (1940 - 1944)|journal=Cahiers Jaurès|date=2014|volume=1|issue=211|pages=95–114|url=http://www.cairn.info/article.php?ID_ARTICLE=CJ_211_0095&DocId=89069&hits=7140+7139+6683+6682+|accessdate=August 12, 2016|via=[[Cairn.info]]|registration=yes}}</ref> By 1931, he suggested he preferred peace to war, even if France had to be invaded by Germany.<ref name="lepacifisme12"/>

Challaye was the author of many books on philosophy. He also published children's books under the pseudonym of Robert Fougère.<ref name="bnf"/>

==Death and legacy==
Challaye died on April 26, 1967 in Paris, France.<ref name="bnf"/> The ''rue Félicien Challaye'' in [[Tunis]], Tunisia was named in his honor.<ref>Google Maps</ref>

