'''Hikmat al-muta‘aliya fi-l-asfar al-‘aqliyya al-arba‘a''' (Arabic:الحکمه المتعالیه فی الاسفار العقلیه الاربعه), known as ''Asfar'', is an extended compendium of [[Islamic philosophy]] written by the 17th century Islamic scholar, [[Mulla Sadra]].<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mulla-sadra/ "Mulla Sadra"] in ''Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy'' at Plato website 9 June Accessed 25 November 2016.</ref> The title means, "Transcendent Philosophy on the Four Intellectual Journeys". The book was first published in print in 1865 in [[Tehran]] in four volumes, where it was accompanied by a commentary on three of the volumes by [[Hadi Sabzavari]] (1797{{ndash}}1893). To date, no notable, critical [[English language|English]] translation of the book has been made.<ref name="Nasr 2006">Nasr H. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Y0ZFkdlCFnYC&dq=Islamic+philosophy+from+its+origins+to+the+present&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Islamic Philosophy from Its Origin to the Present: Philosophy in the Land of Prophecy''] State University of New York Press, 2006. {{ISBN|0791481557}} Accessed 18 July 2017.</ref>{{rp|p. 355}} 

==Author==
{{main|Mulla Sadra}}
'''Mulla Sadrā''' (Ṣadr ad-Dīn Muḥammad Shīrāzī ({{lang-fa|ملا صدرا}}); Molla Sadra; Mollasadra; or Sadr-ol-Mote'allehin; ({{lang-ar|صدرالمتألهین}})) (c. 1571 CE{{ndash}}1640 CE), was an [[Iranian philosophy|Iranian]] [[Shia]] [[Islamic philosophy|Islamic philosopher]], [[Kalam|theologian]] and ''[[Ulama|‘Ālim]]'' (scholar). He was a prominent figure in the [[Iran]]ian cultural [[renaissance]] of the 17th century. [[Oliver Leaman]] of the [[University of Kentucky]] calls Mulla Sadra "the most important and influential philosopher of the last four hundred years in the Muslim world".<ref name="Leaman 2013">Leaman O. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=IxHfaMfRkXYC&dq=mulla+sadra+leaman&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Islamic Philosophy''] John Wiley and Sons, 2013 {{ISBN|0745659071}}</ref>{{rp|p. 146}}<ref>Cooper J. [http://www.muslimphilosophy.com/ip/rep/H027.htm ''Sadr al-Din Muhammad al-Shirazi,1571/2-1640''] Muslim Philosophy website.</ref> Mulla Sadra's writing style is analytic and critical.<ref name="Kamal 2010">Kamal M. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=FAQFMSKwRawC&dq=%27%27From+Essence+to+Being:+The+Philosophy+of+Mulla+Sadra+and+Martin+Heidegger%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''From Essence to Being: The Philosophy of Mulla Sadra and Martin Heidegger''] ICAS Press, 2010 {{ISBN|1904063373}}</ref>{{rp|p. 31}}

==Title==
The complete title of the book is ''Al Hikmat Al Motaaliyyah fi Al Asfar Al Aghliyyah al Arbeah'' which means, "Transcendent Philosophy on the Four Intellectual Journeys".<ref name="Rustom 2012">Rustom M. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=8fo8AAAAQBAJ&dq=%27%27The+Triumph+of+Mercy:+Philosophy+and+Scripture+in+Mulla+Sadra%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''The Triumph of Mercy: Philosophy and Scripture in Mulla Sadra''] State University of New York Press, 2012 {{ISBN|1438443412}}</ref>{{rp|p. 10}} Mulla Sadra's [[transcendent theosophy]] drew from [[Kalam|Kalam wisdom]], [[Illuminationism|Ishraqi philosophy]] and peripatetic philosophy. In [[Arabic]], the word "asfar" means "journey". Mulla Sadra indicated four journeys of man. The book is sometimes referred to as ''Asfar''. It is also sometimes referred to as ''Hekmate Motaalyyah''. However, the book is not to be confused with ''Al Masa'el Al Qodsiyah''.<ref>Moris Z. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3WwAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=Hikmat+Al+Muta'aliyah&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiX18-tucrLAhXhC5oKHeHiArAQ6AEILTAD#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Revelation, Intellectual Intuition and Reason in the Philosophy of Mulla Sadra: an Analysis of the Al-hikmah Al-'arshiyyah''] Routledge, 2013 p. 85 {{ISBN|1136858598}} Accessed 25 November 2016.</ref>

==Key concepts==
''Asfar'' is representative of the greater part of Mulla Sadra's philosophical scholarship.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/biography/Mulla-Sadra Mulla Sadra] Britannica website 20 July 1998. Accessed 20 July 1998.</ref> In its nine volumes, ''Asfar'' examines the philosophical opinions of the different schools of Islamic philosophy. In fact, the compendium acts as a history of Islamic philosophies.<ref>Rizvi S. H. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Ojj60smPREcC&dq=%27%27Mulla+Sadra+and+Metaphysics:+Modulation+of+Being%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Mulla Sadra and Metaphysics: Modulation of Being''] Routledge, 2013 {{ISBN|1134008570}} Accessed 25 November 2013.</ref>

Mulla Sadra's work considers the nature of [[reality]]. It strives to connect [[essentialism]] and [[existentialism]].<ref name="Kalam 2016">Kamal M. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Cd0GDAAAQBAJ&dq=%27%27Mulla+Sadra%27s+Transcendent+Philosophy%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy''] Routledge, 2016 {{ISBN|1317093704}}</ref>{{rp|p. 9 and 39}} Mulla Sadra's [[existentialism]] concerns [[cosmology]] as it pertains to [[Allah]]. His work synthesizes [[Avicennism]], [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]]'s [[Illuminationist philosophy]], [[Ibn Arabi]]'s [[Sufi metaphysics]], and the [[Kalam|theology]] of the [[Ash'ari]] school and [[Twelvers]].<ref name="Leaman 2013"/>{{rp|p. 146-147}}<ref name="Rustom 2012"/>{{rp|p. 114}}

In the first volume of ''Asfar'', Mulla Sadra focuses solely on an analysis of the concept of ''wujud'' ("being") and [[quiddity]] (essence).<ref name="Nasr 2006"/>{{rp|p. 294}} The first volume has four "journeys". The first journey is concerned with the ontology or the doctrine of being. The second journey is concerned with substance and accidents. The third journey deals with God and his attributes and the fourth journey is about the soul of man and a discussion of man, his destiny, death and resurrection.<ref name="Rahman 1975">Rahman F. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=BN0wmwk3LK0C&dq=%27%27The+Philosophy+of+Mulla+Sadra%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''The Philosophy of Mulla Sadra Shirazi''] State University of New York Press, 1975 {{ISBN|0873953002}}</ref>{{rp|p. 19}}

In the tenth section of the third journey of ''Asfar'', Mulla Sadra expresses his opinion on the creation of world. He clarifies the meaning of the word "universe" and its place in time. Mulla Sadra says previous philosophers' premises and conclusions about the concept of eternity are correct. However, he says, the eternity of the world is not derived from them.<ref name="Herrmann 2009">Herrmann R. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hZgkTIWEnp4C&dq=Humanity%27s+Vision+of+God%27%27&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Expanding Humanity's Vision of God''] Templeton Foundation Press, 2009 {{ISBN|1599470977}} Accessed 25 November 2016.</ref>{{rp|p. 159}}  

Mulla Sadra advocates a pantheistic doctrine of existence. He also says that God must have a pure existence.<ref name="Rahman 1975"/> Mulla Sadra points out the differences in his conclusions on this topic compared to those of [[Avicenna]].<ref name="Kalam 2016"/>{{rp|p. 99}}

==Glossaries and commentaries==
Mirza Mahdi Ashtiyyani has made glossaries for ''Asfar''.<ref name="Nasr 2006"/> In 1958, [[Muhammad_Husayn_Tabataba'i|Allameh Muhammad Hosein Tabatabae'i]] and Allameh Muzaffar edited the book in a new version presented in nine volumes. In 1974, Javad Mosleh translated ''Asfar'' into [[Persian language|Persian]]. In 1989, Ayatullah Abdullah Javadi-Amoli published a commentary in Persian entitled ''Raheeq-e Makhtum''.<ref name="Kamal 2010"/>{{rp|p. 31}}

